We have that $BD = 15$ and $BC = 17,$ so $CD = \sqrt{BC^2 - BD^2} = 8.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,0);
B = (0,12);
C = (9,0) + 8*dir(36.87);
D = (9,0);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D);
draw(rightanglemark(B,D,C,20));

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NW);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$12$", (A + B)/2, W);
label("$15$", (B + D)/2, NE);
label("$8$", (C + D)/2, S);
label("$17$", (B + C)/2, NE);
[/asy]

Then the area of quadrilateral $ABCD$ is
\[[ABD] + [BCD] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AB \cdot BD + \frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot CD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 12 \cdot 15 + \frac{1}{2} \cdot 17 \cdot 8 = \boxed{166}.\]

We have \begin{align*}
\text{Area}(ABCD)&=\text{Area}(ABD)+\text{Area}(BCD)\\
&=\frac{1}{2}(AB)(BD)+\frac{1}{2}(BC)(BD)\\
&=\frac{1}{2}(15)(12+17)\\
&=\boxed{172.5}.
\end{align*}

We use the Pythagorean Theorem to find that $AD = \sqrt{BD^2 - AB^2} = 9$ units.  Therefore, the area of triangle $ABD$ is $\frac{1}{2}(AB)(AD) = 54$ square units.  Similarly, the area of triangle $CBD$ is $\frac{1}{2}(BC)(CD) = 68$ square units.

